You need to carry a full-sized pistol behind your hip, you don't want to wear a jacket or your shirt tail out, you want stationary holster placement, and you want total concealment.

That's a lot to ask, but one Federal LE agency and many CCW customers asked. Galco delivered, with our SkyOps™ tuckable concealment holster.

The challenge was to design a belt attachment that provides secure carry at the desired angle while remaining inconspicuous. With a J-Hook or C-Hook, the holster can tilt and dive. While a pair of loops on either side or a single, wide loop around the belt can provide stability, they can also advertise "Gun!" to observers across the room. The solution is the patented Galco Y-Hook™, premiered on our SkyOps holster. The Y-Hook grips as securely as a full loop, yet disappears to all but the most trained eye when worn on a black belt.

The SkyOps will not win the competition for easy on-and-off, nor for quick draw and re-holstering. title: For Sale:  SKS Prince 50 Front Sight- For making regular SKS into Paratrooper model
location: SW Raleigh, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: Brand new Prince 50 front sight for SKS. Some people are converting their long barreled SKS rifles into the shorter 16" barrel that the SKS Paratrooper has. It makes them easier to stow, and a lot of people feel they are more balanced at that length without any change in accuracy. It's legal and fairly easy to cut and crown barrels (as long as you don't go shorter than 16"), and this sight was manufactured to attach simply and easily to the end of the shorter barrel, a whole lot easier than dealing with detaching the original front sight and trying to adapt it to the tapered barrel through machining.  I was going to cut down my barrel, but ended up buying a Paratrooper model, so now I'm selling the sight, and also my longer SKS rifle (in a separate listing on Armslist). The sight is $50, and well worth it if you want to shorten your barrel. Price is firm, as this was fairly expensive. Lower offers will not be replied to.

postcontent:
I was very disappointed today when I arrived at Fleet Farm and stumbled upon this scene.
The shelves were full of Pistol Ammo. Those big blue boxes, 250 or 350 rounds don't remember. There was a sign that clearly said there was a limit of ONE box per customer, and customers there were many. But that did not bother you. You put three cases of shells in your cart and told the rest of us you were going to call your friends and have them come down there to pick up the other boxes. Nevermind the other gentlemen patiently waiting their turns to make a selection, you just took the last three boxes.

Almost EVERY SINGLE TIME I go to that Fleet Farm I meet new, friendly, like-minded individuals in the gun/ammo area. Today I am ashamed to think that I have anything in common with someone who would behave as you did, someone who thinks like you do.

Gun owners, as a group, have a lot of work ahead of us. The behavior you displayed today leaves me concerned, there are people out there who know you, and to them, you are a 'gun guy'. Hopefully they know more than one, because you sir are a poor representative of the outstanding men and women I have met in the shooting sports.

So, fuck you buddy.
